            "id": "f7369e2a9c2d493e811f5",
            "questionText": "A research team is designing a nuclear reactor using Thorium as fuel. They are focused on efficiently achieving critical mass and sustaining a chain reaction. A moderator is used to slow down neutrons, enhancing the probability of further fission. The reactor's core is designed to operate at a power level where each fission event releases approximately $!$200 MeV$!$. Given that the core contains $!$1000 kg$!$ of Thorium and that Thorium has a molar mass of approximately $!$232 g/mol$!$, what is the minimum amount of moderator material (in $!$kg$!$) required to ensure the reactor can sustain a continuous chain reaction at $!$50\\%$!$ of its maximum potential, assuming the moderator has a neutron absorption cross-section of $!$0.01 barns$!$ and the Thorium has a fission cross-section of $!$2 barns$!$? Also, the density of the moderator material is $!$1 g/cm^3$!$.",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "9c3c8331051446a2b3c1c",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by converting the mass of thorium into moles. In order to do that, you need to identify the correct conversion formula from mass (in grams) to moles using the molar mass. Please select the correct formula.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "d28b5c5e-7617-4d12-93c5-491614507352",
                        "b4cc2d1a-f724-4aa8-ae80-2b2e74431f34"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$n = \\frac{mass}{molar~mass}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
